 <H1>Structure</H1> 
 <P><UL>
<LI>main uses of an anchor
<UL>
<LI>provide a destination object within presentation when used with links
<LI>attach temporal  and spatial relations
<LI>text anchor-sequence of characters
</UL><LI>anchors can also specify parts of groups of items 
<UL>
<LI>For example, the word "houses" might be a <b>text anchor</b>
,picture of many houses,<b> an image anchor</b>, and the Dutch word
"huizen" part of a <b>sound anchor</b>.
 
</UL><LI>As well as defining the extent of media item via anchors, they
can also have 
<UL>
<LI> attributes 
<UL>
<LI>which can be used for labeling the parts of the media item 
they refer to, which leads to attaching information to media
items which can be used for retrieval of items (will be 
discussed more later on)</UL></UL></UL></P> <P></P> 



